===Etymology===
From French ''accolade'', from Provençal ''[[acolada]]'', from Italian ''[[accolata]]'', from ''[[accollare]]'' to [[embrace]], from Latin ''[[ad-]]'' + ''[[collum]]'' "neck".

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}
# A [[salutation]] marking the [[conferring]] of [[knighthood]], consisting of an [[embrace]] or a [[kiss]], and a slight blow on the shoulders with the flat of a sword.
# {{music}} A brace used to join two or more [[staves]].
# (an) Expression of praise for achievement.
# {{rfv-sense}} (American Military) Written Presidential certificate recognizing service by personnel who died or were wounded in action between [[1917]] and [[1918]], or who died in service between [[1941]] and [[1947]], or died of wounds received in [[Korea]] between [[June 27]], [[1950]] and [[July 27]], [[1954]]. Service of civilians who died overseas or as a result of injury or disease contracted while serving in a civilian capacity with the United States Armed Forces during the dates and/or in areas prescribed is in like manner recognized.

